	     <form action=/cgi-bin/mrate.pl name=f99295641356185>
	     <tr><td id=headerrow colspan=2 class=mform valign=top><a name=classes.html?class=3&mid=99295641356185>&nbsp;</a><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=3&mid=99295641356185>RE: Money~~~ Equipment</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=3&mid=99295641356185#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a>
	     <br clear=all><small>Posted @ Tue, Jun 19th 9:13 AM 2001</small></td></tr>
	     <tr><td valign=top id=fs8 class=mform><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=67705><span id=Sage>Kensuke</span></a><br><b><span id=Sage>Sage</span></b><br><span id=notbold>85 posts<br><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Decent [3.00]</td><td valign=top class=mform width=100%><p>Wu's armor can be bought in the East Commons, if you're patient. At least on the Rathe, there tends to be one or two usual people who commonly make the items and sell them... it's just a matter of you being there the same time they are. I just finally completed my Wu set just yesterday, after about three weeks of trying to get every piece. Most of the big pieces tend to go for around 75pp's each. The smaller pieces, wrists, face, neck, head, should go for much less. Also, I don't know if it's different on other servers, but at least on the Rathe, there's a merchant right near the bank in North Freeport that sells Wu's fighting cap, so that might be a shortcut for you. <br><br>As for now, if you're short on money, go with cured silk, I'd say. And if you want fast money (the loot at our level is horrid, especially considering we can't solo anything with good loot yet) you might want to take up Baking. I'm sure others will disagree with me, but I think this is the best money making skill for a young character. It's not exciting, it's not thrilling, but at our level, it makes money faster then most of the other trade skills. Just try to max out your baking skill by making edible goo (rat ears, fire beetle eyes) and then batwing crunchies (batwings, frosting) and then fish-fillets, which is the money maker. For the edible goo and batwing crunchies, all of the components can be bought from merchants in East Commons (1st and 3rd inn, respectively.) Fish fillets yield 2 for every 1 fish and 1 jug of sauces you use, and 20 fish fillets sell for 1 plat back to the merchant. So a full stack of 20 fish and 20 jugs will bring in about 2 plats. My strategy is to carry two backpack, two large sacks, go to one merchant, fill up my sacks and bags with one component, and then go to the other merchant, and buy one stack of the other component, and sit there and keep buying and selling back, until all components are gone. Once I'm done with all of the components, which usually takes about 15 minutes or so, if I'm fast, I'm 30 pp's richer. <br><br>Rinse and repeat. <br><br>It's not thrilling. It's not exciting. But it works. At least for now. </p>&nbsp;<br> </td></td></tr>
