	     <table class=mform  border=0 cellpadding=1 cellspacing=0 width=100%>
	     <form action=/cgi-bin/mrate.pl name=f99289112339608>
	     <tr><td id=headerrow colspan=2 class=mform valign=top><a name=classes.html?class=3&mid=99289112339608>&nbsp;</a><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=3&mid=99289112339608>RE: Chat terms</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=3&mid=99289112339608#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a>
	     <br clear=all><small>Posted @ Mon, Jun 18th 3:05 PM 2001</small></td></tr>
	     <tr><td valign=top id=fs8 class=mform><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=2076><span id=Sage>Pusbag</span></a><br><b><span id=Sage>Sage</span></b><br><span id=notbold>1380 posts<br><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Good [4.10]</td><td valign=top class=mform width=100%><p>I might be wrong, but my understanding of the term "proc" stems from the word "produce" (as in a weapon produces an area effect, for instance).&nbsp;&nbsp;Just FYI, high dexterity is what causes involuntary procs to fire off.<br><br>As for "twinking", the term originally was a derogatory slap directed towards someone who unashamedly loaded a new character with items they had not earned themselves.  When the game first came out twinking was socially unacceptable for the most part, but as more people gained higher level chars the need to dispose of good equipment gotten from respawning mobs without selling it to vendors was a problem.  Twinking became common, possibly even necessary as additions to EQ came out.  Now it is rare to find an untwinked character playing the game.<br><br>--Pusbag Infection, King of the Trolls</p>&nbsp;<br>Emperor and Shamanic High Priest of the Trolls<br>"Worship Innoruuk, you worthless cattle!"<br></td></td></tr>
